in .htaccess

2) Change the base URL (which you are doing now) in your .htaccess file. Use a separate .htaccess for each server. So in your local .htaccess, you will set the baseURL as you are doing now, and on your remote .htaccess, you will not set a base URL (as it won't be necessary, as you will be linking from the webroot instead of a subfolder).
3)
basically you need two things done, editing your hosts file, and setting up a virtualhost . The hosts file on your system needs to be edited to point to your localhost. So if you are building www.example.com, you can set up your hosts file to point the domain example.me to point to your local computer. This way any requests made to the domain will then be made to your local server. You will create a virtualhost in your httpd.conf file (if you are using Apache, other systems may vary), that will direct requests for example.me pages to a folder on your local system.

 create a new local domain for every project i'm working on. That way my local machine always most closely resembles my remote machine.

